            <section class="mt-10 prose prose-sm md:prose">
              <h2>How this smoking cost calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool combines the strengths of many public smoking cost
                calculators and adds extra flexibility: you can model
                cigarettes, vaping, or both, adjust how many days per week you
                smoke, and include optional healthcare and productivity losses.
                It also estimates the present value of your future smoking costs
                using a discount rate, a concept borrowed from financial
                planning.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Direct cost of cigarettes</h3>
              <p>
                For cigarettes, we first compute your average number of
                cigarettes smoked per day over the whole week, then multiply by
                the cost per cigarette.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Average cigarettes per day (7-day week)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{avg\_cigs\_per\_day} =
                  \text{cigs\_per\_day\_on\_smoking\_days} \times
                  \frac{\text{smoking\_days\_per\_week}}{7} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Cost per cigarette</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{cost\_per\_cig} =
                  \frac{\text{price\_per\_pack}}{\text{cigs\_per\_pack}} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Direct daily cost</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{daily\_cost} = \text{avg\_cigs\_per\_day} \times
                  \text{cost\_per\_cig} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                From the daily cost we derive weekly, monthly, and yearly costs
                using:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Weekly cost = daily cost × 7</li>
                <li>
                  Monthly cost ≈ daily cost × 30.4 (average days per month)
                </li>
                <li>Yearly cost = daily cost × 365</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                We then add your “other smoking costs per month” (lighters,
                filters, rolling papers, etc.) to the monthly and yearly totals.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Direct cost of vaping</h3>
              <p>
                For vaping, we estimate how many milliliters of e-liquid you use
                per day and how much that costs.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Average ml per day (7-day week)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{avg\_ml\_per\_day} =
                  \text{ml\_per\_day\_on\_vaping\_days} \times
                  \frac{\text{vaping\_days\_per\_week}}{7} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Cost per ml</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{cost\_per\_ml} =
                  \frac{\text{price\_per\_bottle}}{\text{bottle\_size\_ml}} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Direct daily vaping cost</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{daily\_vape\_cost} = \text{avg\_ml\_per\_day} \times
                  \text{cost\_per\_ml} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                As with cigarettes, we convert this to weekly, monthly, and
                yearly costs and add any extra monthly vaping expenses (coils,
                pods, batteries).
              </p>

              <h3>3. Combining cigarettes and vaping</h3>
              <p>
                If you use both cigarettes and vaping products, the calculator
                simply adds the direct costs from each source plus your combined
                “other” monthly costs:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{total\_direct\_daily} = \text{cig\_daily\_cost} +
                  \text{vape\_daily\_cost} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{total\_direct\_monthly} = \text{cig\_monthly} +
                  \text{vape\_monthly} + \text{other\_monthly} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Indirect costs: healthcare and productivity</h3>
              <p>
                Research from public health agencies and economic studies
                consistently shows that the total economic burden of smoking is
                much larger than the money spent on tobacco products alone. It
                includes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Higher healthcare spending (doctor visits, medications,
                  hospital stays)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Lost productivity (sick days, smoke breaks, reduced work
                  performance)
                </li>
                <li>Premature mortality and reduced quality of life</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                To keep the tool simple and transparent, we let you enter your
                own estimates for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Extra healthcare cost per year related to smoking</li>
                <li>
                  Productivity loss per year (lost income or value of time)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>These are then added to your direct yearly smoking cost:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{indirect\_per\_year} = \text{healthcare\_per\_year} +
                  \text{productivity\_per\_year} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{total\_per\_year} = \text{direct\_per\_year} +
                  \text{indirect\_per\_year} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Lifetime cost and present value</h3>
              <p>
                To estimate the lifetime cost of smoking, you choose how many
                more years you expect to continue smoking at the same rate. The
                calculator multiplies your yearly cost by this number of years:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Nominal lifetime cost</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{lifetime\_nominal} = \text{total\_per\_year} \times
                  \text{years\_smoking} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Because money in the future is worth less than money today, we
                also compute the
                <em>present value</em> of your future smoking costs using a
                discount rate you can adjust:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Present value of an annual cost stream</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{PV} = \text{total\_per\_year} \times \frac{1 - (1 +
                  r)^{-n}}{r} \]
                </p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( r \) = annual discount rate (e.g. 0.03 for 3%)</li>
                  <li>\( n \) = number of years you expect to keep smoking</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is the same formula used in retirement and investment
                planning to compare future cash flows in today’s dollars.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Potential savings if you quit</h3>
              <p>
                Finally, the calculator estimates how much money you could free
                up if you quit smoking now:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Monthly savings</strong> ≈ your current total monthly
                  smoking cost
                </li>
                <li><strong>5-year savings</strong> ≈ total yearly cost × 5</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This does not assume any investment returns. If you invested
                those savings, the long-term benefit could be significantly
                larger.
              </p>

