</ul>
              <p>
                Public health data from organizations such as the CDC, ASH, and
                national health services show that smoking is one of the most
                expensive lifestyle habits when you combine direct spending and
                indirect costs. Quitting can quickly become one of the best
                “investments” you ever make.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and responsible use</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Prices and taxes change.</strong> Tobacco taxes and
                  product prices can rise faster than general inflation, so your
                  future costs may be higher than shown.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Health impacts are individual.</strong> The healthcare
                  and productivity estimates are simplified and may not reflect
                  your personal situation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Not medical advice.</strong> This calculator is for
                  educational and planning purposes only and does not replace
                  advice from a healthcare professional.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is vaping always cheaper than smoking?</h3>
              <p>
                Not necessarily. While many people spend less on vaping than on
                cigarettes, heavy e-liquid use, premium devices, and frequent
                coil or pod replacements can add up. This calculator lets you
                compare your own patterns side by side.
              </p>

              <h3>What discount rate should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                A discount rate between 2–5% is common in personal finance to
                reflect inflation and the opportunity cost of money. A higher
                rate reduces the present value of future costs; a lower rate
                increases it. If you are unsure, leaving the default value is
                reasonable.
              </p>

              <h3>Where can I get help to quit smoking?</h3>
              <p>
                If you are thinking about quitting, consider speaking with your
                doctor, pharmacist, or a local stop-smoking service. Many
                countries offer free quitlines, counselling, and medications to
                support you. Combining financial motivation with professional
                support can significantly increase your chances of success.
              </p>
